Binary Classification Task Using Tsetlin Machine (TM)

executive summary

the aim of this project is to make binary classification using tsetling machine for a telecomunication company called telco and compare it uses with three traditional machine learning algorithm which are decision tree,random forest and logistic regression.the most important metric to access this data is the recall function and the second most important is the f1 score

1. introduction

telco is a telecomunication company which aim to classify their data using tsetling machine. in this project we will use tree main metrics to compare the models , those metrics are recall score , f1 score and precision

function to fill null value with the best central measure between mean and median

In[171]:
def central_tendancy_calculator(a,column):
#replacing dollar sign and converting to float if necessary
  try:
    # Remove dollar signs and commas, then convert to float
    a[column] = a[column].str.replace(r'[$,]', '', regex=True).astype(float)
  except Exception as e:
    print(f"Error converting column {column}: {e}")
# remove missing value to make calculation
  dataset=pd.DataFrame()
  dataset[column]=a[column].dropna()



#calculate mean
  mean=reduce(add,dataset[column] )/len(dataset[column] )

#calculate interquatile ranges to check the outliers


  Q1 = dataset[column] .quantile(0.25)# Calculate Q1 (25th percentile)
  Q3 = dataset[column] .quantile(0.75)# CalculateQ3 (75th percentile)

  # Calculate the IQR
  IQR = Q3 - Q1

  # Determine the lower and upper bounds for outliers
  lower_bound = Q1 - 1.5 * IQR
  upper_bound = Q3 + 1.5 * IQR

  # Identify outliers

  outliers= (dataset[column]  < lower_bound) | (dataset[column]  > upper_bound)
# calculate median (median is better when the dataset have outliers)
  median= dataset[column].median()
# calculate the mode
  mode=dataset[column].mode()
# calculate skewness
  Skewness=dataset[column].skew()
#calculate variance
  variance=dataset[column].var()
# print result
  # print mean
  print(f"the mean is {mean}")
  # print meddian
  print(f"the median is {median}")
  # print mode
  print(f"the mode is {mode}")
  # print variance
  print(f"the variance is {variance}")
  # print Skewness
  print(f"the skewness is {Skewness}")
  # Print only the outliers
  print("Outliers using IQR method:")
  print( dataset[outliers].count() )

  if int(dataset[outliers].count())==0 and (Skewness>=-0.5 or Skewness<=0.5) :
    print("null value will be fill with the mean")
    a[column].fillna(mean, inplace=True)
  else:
     print("null value will be fill with the median")
     a[column].fillna(median, inplace=True)

def mode_calculator(a,column):
    # remove missing value to make calculation
  dataset=pd.DataFrame()
  dataset[column]=a[column].dropna()
  # calculate the mode
  mode=dataset[column].mode()
   # print mode
  print(f"the mode is {mode}")
  a[column].fillna(str(mode), inplace=True)

important insight from above diagram

  • in the second line we can se the gender distribution with male represent by yes and female by no. we observe that 50.5% of the customer are male and 49.5% are female
  • the average number of month customer stay in the company is 32 with a std of 24.5 which mean that the data are widely spread awayfrom the mean and that there is a high variability. but half of the customer stay mor than 29 month
  • 90% of the customer have Phone Service and around 78% of them have internet service
  • more than half of the customer contract are montly-monthly , the average customer pay around 65 montly and half of the customer pay more than 70 monthly
  • 26.6% of the customer churn

churn distribution

in this part shows the visualization of the churk by each charateristic

function to drawnn a bar chart of churn by another metriic

In[211]:
def churn_by(df,b,a="Churn",):
    gender_df=df[b].value_counts()
    gender_churn = df[df[a] == 'Yes'][b].value_counts()
    gender_churn = gender_churn.reindex(gender_df.index, fill_value=0)
    percent_churn = (gender_churn / gender_df) * 100
    gender_churn_df= pd.DataFrame({
        b: gender_df,
        a: gender_churn
    })
    ax=gender_churn_df.plot(kind='bar', color=['blue','red'])
    ax.set_xticklabels(gender_churn_df.index, rotation=0)

    plt.xlabel(b)
    plt.ylabel('Count')
    plt.title('Distribution of Scores by Gender')
    plt.legend(title='bar description')
    plt.show()
    print(f"the churn rate percentage of {b}")
    print(percent_churn)

function to show machine performance

In[239]:
def performence(y_test,y_predicted , a):
  print(sklearn.metrics.classification_report(y_test, y_predicted))
  confusion_matrix = sklearn.metrics.confusion_matrix(y_test, y_predicted)

  if a==1:
    cm_display = sklearn.metrics.ConfusionMatrixDisplay(confusion_matrix = confusion_matrix, display_labels = ["retention", "Churn"])

    cm_display.plot()

COMPARING ALGORITHM

in this part we will compare basic setting performance of tsetlin machine with logistic regression , random forest,decision tree

The key metrics to compare this algorithm are recall_score,f1_score and precision_score. we have to maximise the Recall as we want the model to focuse correctly detecte the potential churn. and secondly focuse on f1 score to balance precison and recall

split data
